 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 128) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Various studies have concluded that an organization's human resources can be a significant source of competitive advantage. And that's true for organizations around the world. The Human Capital Index, a comprehensive study of over 2,000 firms in North America, Europe, and the Asia\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Pacific region conducted by consulting firm Watson Wyatt Worldwide concluded that people\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 oriented HR gives an organization an edge by creating superior shareholder value. Achieving competitive success through people requires a fundamental change in how managers think about their employees and how they view the work relationship. It involves working with and through people and seeing them as partners, not just as costs to be minimized or avoided. That's what people\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 oriented organizations do. In addition to being an important part of organizational strategy and contributing to competitive advantage, an organization's HRM practices have been found to have a significant impact on organizational performance. For instance, one study reported that significantly improving an organization's HRM practices could increase its market value by as much as 30 percent. Another study that tracked average annual shareholder returns of the publicly traded companies on \i Fortune\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 's list of 100 best companies to work for found that these companies significantly beat the S&P 500 over 10\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 year, 5\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 year, 3\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 year, and 1\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 year periods. High\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 performance work practices lead to both high individual and high organizational performance. The common thread in these practices seems to be a commitment to improving the knowledge, skills, and abilities of an organization's employees, increasing their motivation, reducing loafing on the job, and enhancing the retention of quality employees while encouraging low performers to leave. Even if an organization chooses not to implement high\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 performance work practices, there are certain HRM activities that must be completed in order to ensure that the organization has qualified people to perform the work that needs to be done\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 activities that comprise the human resource management process.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 129) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Future human resource needs are determined by the organization's mission, goals\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 and strategies. Demand for employees is a result of demand for the organization's\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 products or services. Once managers have assessed both current capabilities and future needs, they\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 can estimate areas in which the organization will be understaffed or overstaffed.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 With this information, managers are ready to proceed to the next step in the HRM\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 process.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 130) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Job analysis is an assessment that defines jobs and the behaviors necessary to perform them. Information for a job analysis can be gathered through the following methods\: directly observing or filming individuals on the job, interviewing employees individually or in a group, having employees complete a structured questionnaire, having job "experts" identify a job's specific characteristics, and having employees record their daily activities in a diary or notebook. With information from the job analysis, managers develop or revise job descriptions and job specifications. A job description is a written statement of what a jobholder does, how it is done, and why it is done. It typically describes job content, environment, and conditions of employment. A job specification states the minimum qualifications that a person must possess to perform a given job successfully. It identifies the knowledge, skills, and attitudes needed to do the job effectively. Both the job description and specification are important documents when managers begin recruiting and selecting.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 131) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx340 1.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Internet\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 the advantages are that this source can reach large numbers of people and can get immediate feedback. The disadvantage is that it generates many unqualified candidates.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx340 2.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Employee referrals\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 the advantages include the fact that knowledge about the organization may be provided by current employees, and that they can generate strong candidates because a good referral reflects on the recommender. A disadvantage is that this source may not increase the diversity and mix of employees.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx340 3.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Internal source\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 the advantages include low cost, builds employee morale, and candidates are familiar with the organization. The disadvantages include limited supply and this source may not increase the proportion of employees from protected groups.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx340 4.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Company website\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 the advantages include wide distribution and this source can be targeted to specific groups. A major disadvantage is that it may generate many unqualified candidates.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx340 5.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 College recruiting\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 one advantage is that there is a large centralized body of candidates. The disadvantage is this source is limited to entry\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 level positions.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx340 6.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Professional recruiting organizations\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 the advantage is that the candidates have a good knowledge of industry challenges and requirements. The disadvantage is candidates have little commitment to the specific organization.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 132) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 a.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 The Application Form\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 almost all organizations require job candidates to fill out an application. It may be only a form on which the person gives his or her name, address, and telephone number. Or it might be a comprehensive personal history profile, detailing the person's activities, skills, and accomplishments. \ul Strength\:\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  contains relevant biographical data and facts that can be verified and have been shown to be valid performance measures for some jobs. \ul Weakness\:\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  usually only a couple of items on the form prove to be valid predictors of job performance and then only for specific jobs.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 b.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Written tests\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 typical types of written tests include tests for intelligence, aptitude, ability, and interest. Such tests have been used for years, although their popularity tends to run in cycles. Today, personality, behavioral, and aptitude assessment tests are popular among businesses. \ul Strength\:\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  intelligence tests are reasonably good predictors for supervisory positions. \ul Weakness\:\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  intelligence and other tested characteristics can be somewhat removed from actual job performance, thus reducing their validity.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 c.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Performance\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 simulation tests\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 these tests are made up of actual job behaviors. The best\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 known performance\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 simulation tests are work sampling and assessment centers. Work sampling involves presenting applicants with a miniature model of a job and having them perform a task or set of tasks that are central to it. Assessment centers are places in which job candidates undergo performance\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 simulation tests that evaluate managerial potential. \ul Strength\:\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  have proven to be valid predictors of job performance. \ul Weakness\:\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  expensive to create and administer.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 d.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 The Interview\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 like the application form, the interview is an almost universal device. However, the value of the interview as a selection device has been the subject of considerable debate. \ul Strength\:\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  must be structured and well organized to be effective predictors. \ul Weakness\:\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  subject to potential biases, especially if interviews are not well structured and standardized.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 e.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Background investigations\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 these are of two types\: verifications of application data and reference checks. The first type has proved to be a valuable source of selection information whereas the latter is essentially worthless as a selection tool because applicants' references tend to be almost universally positive. \ul Strength\:\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  verifications of background data are valuable sources of information. \ul Weakness\:\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  reference checks are essentially worthless as a selection tool.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 f.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Physical examinations\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 this device would be useful only for a small number of jobs that have certain physical requirements. Instead, the physical examination is mostly used for insurance purposes, as organizations want to be sure that new hires will not submit insurance claims for injuries or illnesses they had before being hired. \ul Strength\:\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  has some validity for jobs with certain physical requirements. \ul Weakness\:\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  must be sure that physical requirements are job related and do not discriminate.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 133) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 When a person starting a new job is introduced to his or her job and the organization, this is called orientation. There are two types of orientation. Work unit orientation familiarizes the employee with the goals of the work unit, clarifies how his or her job contributes to the unit's goals, and includes an introduction to his or her new coworkers. Organization orientation informs the new employee about the company's goals, history, philosophy, procedures, and rules. It should also include relevant human resource policies and maybe even a tour of the facilities. Many organizations, particularly large ones, have formal orientation programs. Others may use a more informal orientation program in which, for instance, the manager assigns the new employee to a senior member of the work group who introduces the new employee to immediate coworkers and shows him or her locations of the copy room, coffee machine, restrooms, cafeteria, and the like. And then there are intense orientation programs that cover everything from the culture of the company to on\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 the\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 job training. Managers have an obligation to make the integration of the new employee into the organization as smooth and as free of anxiety as possible. They need to openly discuss employee beliefs regarding mutual obligations of the organization and the employee. It's in the best interests of the organization and the new employee to get the person up and running in the job as soon as possible. Successful orientation, whether formal or informal, results in an outsider\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 insider transition that makes the new member feel comfortable and fairly well adjusted, lowers the likelihood of poor work performance, and reduces the probability of a surprise resignation by the new employee only a week or two into the job.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 134) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 a.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 On\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 the\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 job\'96employees learn how to do tasks simply by performing them, typically after an initial introduction to the task.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 b.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Job rotation\'96employees work at different jobs in a particular area getting exposure to a variety of tasks.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 c.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Mentoring and coaching\'96employees work with an experienced worker who provides information, support, and encouragement.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 d.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Experiential exercises\'96employees participate in role playing, simulations, or other face\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 to\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 face types of training.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 e.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Workbooks/manuals\'96employees refer to training workbooks and manuals for information.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 f.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Classroom lectures\'96employees attend lectures designed to convey specific information.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 135) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx340 a.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Written essay\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 a technique in which an evaluator writes out a description of an employee's strengths and weaknesses, past performance, and potential. The evaluator also makes suggestions for improvement.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx340 b.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Critical incidents\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 focuses the evaluator's attention on critical or key behaviors that separate effective from ineffective job performance. The appraiser writes down anecdotes that describe what an employee did that was especially effective or ineffective. The advantage to this approach is that only specific behaviors, not vaguely defined personality traits, are cited.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx340 c.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Graphic rating scales\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 this method lists a set of performance factors such as quantity and quality of work, job knowledge, cooperation, initiative, and so forth. The evaluator goes down the list and rates each employee on each factor using an incremental scale.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx340 d.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Behaviorally\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 anchored scales\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 these scales combine major elements from the critical incident and graphic rating scale approaches. The appraiser rates the employee according to items along a numerical scale, but the items are examples of actual job behaviors rather than general descriptions or traits.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx340 e.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Multiperson comparison\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 this approach compares one person's performance with that of others.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx340 f.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 MBO\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Management by objectives is also an effective performance appraisal method. Employees are evaluated on specific goals that were established jointly by them and the manager.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx340 g.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 360\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 degree feedback\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 a method utilizing feedback from supervisors, employees, and coworkers, utilizing information from the full circle of people with whom the manager interacts. Although it's effective for career coaching and helping a manager recognize his or her strengths and weaknesses, it's not appropriate for determining pay, promotions, or terminations.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 136) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 a.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Recruitment\: To improve workforce diversity, managers need to widen their recruiting net. The employee diversity of the Emirates Group is evidenced by its successful Airport Ground Services and Travel Industry division, which comprises employees of over 150 nationalities. As a global organization, Emirates can draw on many resources and locations to improve employee diversity. Talent is not nationality restricted, and the employees' diversity of nationalities, cultures, religions, and ethnic backgrounds enriches their workforce by bringing in new ideas, innovations, and ways of thinking.\plain\f185\fs16\cf0  \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 But not every organization has this choice. Managers may have to look for diverse job applicants in places they might not have looked before\: women's job networks, training centers for disabled individuals, different geographic areas. Such nontraditional recruiting should enable an organization to broaden its pool of diverse applicants.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 b.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Selection\: Once a diverse set of applicants exists, efforts must be made to ensure that the selection process does not discriminate. Moreover, applicants need to be made comfortable with the organization's culture and be made aware of management's desire to accommodate their needs. For instance, a survey published by a Dubai\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 based recruitment firm reported that 75 percent of all job applicants in the energy sector in Gulf countries had faced discrimination while applying for a job. And when asked to name the worst offender, 28.5 percent \'96\'96 the highest figure \'96\'96 directly\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 pointed to the oil industry as being gender biased.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 c.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Orientation and training\: The outsider\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 insider transition is often more challenging for women  and minorities. Many organizations provide special workshops to raise diversity awareness issues for these groups. For instance, with the support of the human resources department, Dubai Aluminium Company Limited (DUBAL) enrolled 16 young women from the UAE for the 2009 intake of its Pre\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Employment Course Administration Program. During their training, the women would undergo training sessions on diverse subjects, including English, PC applications, telephone techniques and management skills (including communications, team management, decision making, influencing, problem solving, meetings, and writing memos).
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 137) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 A \plain\f185\fs20\cf2 labor union \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 is an organization that represents workers and seeks to protect their interests through collective bargaining. In unionized organizations, many HRM decisions are dictated by collective bargaining agreements, which usually define things such as\: recruitment sources; criteria for hiring, promotions, and layoffs; training eligibility; and disciplinary practices. About 12.1 percent of the U.S. workforce is unionized, while the rate is 9.6 percent in France. In Japan, some 19.6 percent of the labor force belongs to a union; in Germany, 27 percent; in Denmark, 75 percent; in Australia, 22.7 percent; in Canada, 30 percent; and in Mexico, 19 percent.  Qatar, Saudi Arabia, and UAE do not have a tradition of labor unions.  However, this is not the case in Lebanon, Syria, Kuwait, Egypt, and Jordan, where employees are authorized to join labor unions. In many of these countries, labor unions are very active. In Lebanon, for example, labor unions often call for strikes and other types of protests to block undesirable government actions or proposed laws.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 138) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\ql\li0\ri0\fi0\sb0\sa0\sl0 Women's work in Arab countries has been traditionally constrained for various cultural and historical reasons. The last few decades, however, have seen fundamental changes in many Arab countries. For women, education and the right to work in jobs such as medicine, teaching, and nursing has become undisputed in most of the Arab world and is allowed in religious circles. Reports on Arab human development indicate that there have been significant improvements pertaining to women's development in the region. However, women in the Arab world continue to suffer from severe limitations on their participation in political, economic, and social life, limited access to employment opportunities, high illiteracy, and wage discrimination. Additional problems include sexual harassment (56% of women working in offices in one Arab country experienced verbal harassment either by managers or colleagues), and the problem of managing a work\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 life balance, particularly where women have sick children to look after, elderly parents to care for, and other family issues that may require special arrangements. \plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \tab \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\ql\li0\ri0\fi0\sb0\sa0\sl0 The situation of working women in Arab states requires the implementation of serious measures to develop their professional status, while at the same time respecting cultural considerations. \plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \tab \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\ql\li0\ri0\fi0\sb0\sa0\sl0 Several steps are suggested for HR managers, including\:\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\ql\li0\ri0\fi0\sb0\sa0\sl0 1. Implement equal employment opportunity policies.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\ql\li0\ri0\fi0\sb0\sa0\sl0 2. Support working women through organizational initiatives, such as child\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 care and flextime arrangements.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\ql\li0\ri0\fi0\sb0\sa0\sl0 3. Provide training to working women equal to the training given to their male counterparts.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\ql\li0\ri0\fi0\sb0\sa0\sl0 4. Work on bridging the pay gap through aggressive pay equity initiatives.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\ql\li0\ri0\fi0\sb0\sa0\sl0 5. Provide educational and training opportunities to all company participants that will highlight the value of women's work in economic and organizational development.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\ql\li0\ri0\fi0\sb0\sa0\sl0 6. Offer serious career development plans for women, taking into consideration the cultural and personal context within which these women live.
}
